Creating a browser-based Minecraft bot using the WSMC (WebSocket Minecraft) plugin API requires a basic understanding of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Below is a simple example of how you can create a web app that connects to a Minecraft server using the WSMC API. This example assumes you have the WSMC plugin set up on your Minecraft server.

Here's a complete HTML file with embedded CSS and JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Minecraft Bot</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        #console {
            background-color: #333;
            color: #fff;
            padding: 10px;
            height: 300px;
            overflow-y: scroll;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            width: calc(100% - 22px);
            padding: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px;
            width: 100%;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Minecraft Bot</h1>
<div id="console"></div>
<input type="text" id="message" placeholder="Type your message here...">
<button id="send">Send Message</button>

<script>
    const serverUrl = 'ws://your.minecraft.server:port'; // Replace with your server's WebSocket URL
    const consoleDiv = document.getElementById('console');
    const messageInput = document.getElementById('message');
    const sendButton = document.getElementById('send');

    const ws = new WebSocket(serverUrl);

    ws.onopen = () => {
        logToConsole('Connected to the Minecraft server.');
    };

    ws.onmessage = (event) => {
        const data = JSON.parse(event.data);
        logToConsole(`Received: ${data.message}`);
    };

    ws.onclose = () => {
        logToConsole('Disconnected from the Minecraft server.');
    };

    sendButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const message = messageInput.value;
        if (message) {
            ws.send(JSON.stringify({ action: 'chat', message: message }));
            logToConsole(`Sent: ${message}`);
            messageInput.value = '';
        }
    });

    function logToConsole(message) {
        const timestamp = new Date().toLocaleTimeString();
        consoleDiv.innerHTML += `<div>[${timestamp}] ${message}</div>`;
        consoleDiv.scrollTop = consoleDiv.scrollHeight; // Auto-scroll to the bottom
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use:
1. **Replace the WebSocket URL**: Change `ws://your.minecraft.server:port` to the actual WebSocket URL of your Minecraft server where the WSMC plugin is running.
2. **Open the HTML File**: Save the code above in a file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `minecraft_bot.html`) and open it in a web browser.
3. **Connect and Send Messages**: Once connected, you can type messages in the input box and click the "Send Message" button to send messages to the Minecraft server.

### Note:
- Ensure that your Minecraft server is running the WSMC plugin and is configured to accept WebSocket connections.
- This is a basic implementation. You can expand it by adding more features like handling different types of messages, commands, or even player actions.

Certainly! Below is a complete HTML file that uses the `mineflayer-ws` library to create a simple web app for connecting to a Minecraft server. This example assumes you have a WebSocket server set up with `mineflayer-ws` that allows you to connect to a Minecraft server.

Here's the code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Minecraft Bot with Mineflayer-WS</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        #console {
            background-color: #333;
            color: #fff;
            padding: 10px;
            height: 300px;
            overflow-y: scroll;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            width: calc(100% - 22px);
            padding: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px;
            width: 100%;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Minecraft Bot with Mineflayer-WS</h1>
<div id="console"></div>
<input type="text" id="message" placeholder="Type your message here...">
<button id="send">Send Message</button>

<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/mineflayer-ws@latest/dist/mineflayer-ws.min.js"></script>
<script>
    const serverUrl = 'ws://your.minecraft.server:port'; // Replace with your WebSocket server URL
    const consoleDiv = document.getElementById('console');
    const messageInput = document.getElementById('message');
    const sendButton = document.getElementById('send');

    const bot = mineflayerWs.createBot({
        host: 'your.minecraft.server', // Replace with your Minecraft server address
        port: 25565, // Replace with your Minecraft server port
        username: 'Bot', // Replace with the bot's username
        version: false, // Set to false to use the latest version
        ws: serverUrl
    });

    bot.on('spawn', () => {
        logToConsole('Connected to the Minecraft server.');
    });

    bot.on('chat', (username, message) => {
        logToConsole(`${username}: ${message}`);
    });

    bot.on('error', (err) => {
        logToConsole(`Error: ${err.message}`);
    });

    bot.on('end', () => {
        logToConsole('Disconnected from the Minecraft server.');
    });

    sendButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const message = messageInput.value;
        if (message) {
            bot.chat(message);
            logToConsole(`Sent: ${message}`);
            messageInput.value = '';
        }
    });

    function logToConsole(message) {
        const timestamp = new Date().toLocaleTimeString();
        consoleDiv.innerHTML += `<div>[${timestamp}] ${message}</div>`;
        consoleDiv.scrollTop = consoleDiv.scrollHeight; // Auto-scroll to the bottom
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use:
1. **Replace the WebSocket URL**: Change `ws://your.minecraft.server:port` to the actual WebSocket URL of your `mineflayer-ws` server.
2. **Replace Server Details**: Update the `host`, `port`, and `username` fields in the `createBot` function with your Minecraft server's details.
3. **Open the HTML File**: Save the code above in a file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `minecraft_bot.html`) and open it in a web browser.
4. **Connect and Send Messages**: Once connected, you can type messages in the input box and click the "Send Message" button to send messages to the Minecraft server.

### Note:
- Ensure that your WebSocket server is running with `mineflayer-ws` and is configured to connect to your Minecraft server.
- This is a basic implementation. You can expand it by adding more features like handling different types of messages, commands, or player actions.
